Predicting Visibility in Ocean Water From Buoy Data¶

What¶

My goal of this project is to see if I can use buoy data from off the Santa Barbara Coast to predict water visibility of the ocean water about fourty meters off of campus point.

Why¶

For as long as I can remember I have always loved diving. What I don't love is getting 40 meters out into the water and realizing that I can't even see my feet in the water. When this happened to me, I tried looking up what causes bad water visibility, and I kept getting different answers. Some people said it was the amount of chlorophyll in the water but the day I went out the levels were very low and I have seen multiple time when high chlorophyll days had great visibilitt. I then decided that I was going to try and find a way to predict the water visibility before I got out there.

How¶

Predicting Water Visibility has been a difficult problem for many people. Almost no buoys and no satelittes measure water visibility directly making it really hard to do any machine learning to predict the visibility. Luckily there is a paper by Keivan Kabiri and Masoud Moradi (citiation at the bottom) that attempts to use the Landsat-8 measured "band values" to predict water visibility. They came up with the equation: $$ SDD = 0.077*e^{1.209B1 - 1.739B2 + 0.412B3 - 5.198(B3/B1) + 10.408(B2/B1)}$$ I use the above equation is a formula for the SDD or Secchi disk depth. This depth is the depth of a Secchi disk before a viewer can no longer see the disk. I will be using this formula as my response variable

For my predictor variables I use the Station 46054 (LLNR 198.1) - WEST SANTA BARBARA 38 NM West of Santa Barbara, CA Buoy. I use the buoy's Standard meteorological data.

First we need to gather all the images from the folder in which I downloaded them all. We will put the images in a dictionary where the keys are the dates that this image was taken

In [36]:
def GetImagesFromFolder(directory, band_number,n_images = 4):
    
    
    #This collects all the subfolders which contain 4 images each. These images are the band values for each
    #Satelitte
    sub_folders = [name for name in os.listdir(directory) if os.path.isdir(os.path.join(directory, name))]
    
    # Creating an empty dictionary
    imagesDict = {}
    
    #For each subfolder we are going to exact the 4 images individually
    for items in sub_folders:
        
        #Creates new directory that goes directly to one image
        new_directory = directory + "/" + items

        count = 0
        
        #List that will hold our files
        listfiles = []
        
        #This for loop just imports all the files for all the images
        for filename in os.listdir(new_directory):
            
            f = os.path.join(new_directory, filename)
            # checking if it is a TIF file and checks if file is the correct band number
            if os.path.isfile(f) and count < n_images and 'B' + str(band_number) + '.TIF' == f[len(f) - 6:]:
                count += 1
                listfiles.append(f)

 
        #Adding list as value
        imagesDict[items] = listfiles
    
    return imagesDict

This code essentially does exactly what our example does

In [39]:
def deriveBandValue(directory,n):
    
    #We use function about to get images
    imageDict = GetImagesFromFolder(directory,n)
    
    imglist = []
    dateList = []
    
    #Puts the dates into a nice readable format
    for keys in imageDict.keys():

        imglist.append(Image.open(imageDict[keys][0]))

        dateList.append(keys[ 0 : 4 ] + '-' + keys[4:6] + '-' + keys[6:8])
        
    # Create the pandas DataFrame with column name is provided explicitly
    df = pd.DataFrame(dateList, columns=['Date'])
        

    box = (3700,4700,4080,4765)
    
    valueList = []

    for x in range(len(imglist)):
        
        region1 = imglist[x].crop(box)
        imglist[x] = region1.resize((400,65))
        
        #Turn image into an array
        img1 = array(imglist[x])
        
        #Threshold Image
        binary_min = img1 > 11000
        
        for i in range(len(binary_min)-1, -1, -1):
            if True in binary_min[i]:
                last_row_with_true = i
                break
            
        for i in range(len(binary_min[:][1])-1, -1, -1):
            if binary_min[last_row_with_true][i] == True:
                last_column_with_true = i
                break
        

        value = img1[last_row_with_true + 7][last_column_with_true]
        
        
        valueList.append(value)
    
    #Labels the dataframe column "Band n"
    df['Band' + str(n)] = valueList
     
    
    return valueList, df

Here we are using the papers formula in order to get an estimates SDD.

In [41]:
#Initiates a list
SDDlist = []

for i in range(len(df['Date'])):
    #We do this since this puts the bands into a form that the paper uses
    b1 = df['Band1'][i] * (1 / 65535) - 0.2 
    b2 = df['Band 2'][i] * (1 / 65535) - 0.2
    b3 = df['Band 3'][i] * (1 / 65535) - 0.2
    
    #Function that is in cited paper
    SDD = 0.077 * np.exp((1.209 * b1) - (1.739 * b2) + (0.412 * b3) - (5.198 * (b3/b1)) + (10.408 * (b2/b1)))
    
    #Adds SDD value to a list
    SDDlist.append(SDD)

#Adds a SDD column
df['SDD'] = SDDlist

#Changes the dataframe so we just have data and SDD value
df = df[['Date','SDD']]
print(df)

dataWhole = []

for X in [2013,2014,2015,2016,2017,2018,2019,2020,2021,2022]:
    
    #Creates a directory for each year of the buoy data and reads it in
    direct = '/Users/jakebentley/buoyData' + str(X) + '.txt'
    data = pd.read_table(direct, delimiter = None)

    Date = []
    hh = []
    mm = []
    WDIR = []
    WSPD = []
    GST = []
    WVHT = []
    DPD = []
    APD = []
    MWD = []
    PRES = []
    ATMP = []
    WTMP = []
    DEWP = []

    #Takes the column name that read_table gives
    for i in range(1,len(data)):
        dataList = data['#YY  MM DD hh mm WDIR WSPD GST  WVHT   DPD   APD MWD   PRES  ATMP  WTMP  DEWP  VIS  TIDE'][i].split(" ")
        #Gets rid of spaces
        dataList = [value for value in dataList if value != '']
        #Extracts all elements
        Date.append(dataList[0] + "-" + dataList[1] + "-" + dataList[2])
        hh.append(dataList[3])
        mm.append(dataList[4])
        WDIR.append(float(dataList[5]))
        WSPD.append(float(dataList[6]))
        GST.append(float(dataList[7]))
        WVHT.append(float(dataList[8]))
        DPD.append(float(dataList[9]))
        APD.append(float(dataList[10]))
        MWD.append(float(dataList[11]))
        PRES.append(float(dataList[12]))
        ATMP.append(float(dataList[13]))
        WTMP.append(float(dataList[14]))
        DEWP.append(float(dataList[15]))
    
    #Creates a dataframe for each year
    weatherDF = pd.DataFrame(Date, columns=['Date'])
    weatherDF['hh'] = hh
    weatherDF['mm'] = mm
    weatherDF['WDIR'] = WDIR
    weatherDF['WSPD'] = WSPD
    weatherDF['GST'] = GST

    weatherDF['APD'] = APD
    weatherDF['MWD'] = MWD
    weatherDF['PRES'] = PRES
    weatherDF['ATMP'] = ATMP
    weatherDF['WTMP'] = WTMP
    weatherDF['DEWP'] = DEWP
    
    #Adds a dataframe as an element to a list
    dataWhole.append(weatherDF)

Now we split data into training data , and testing data. Note we don't stratify be SDD. Doing this brings the error "The least populated class in y has only 1 member, which is too few. The minimum number of groups for any class cannot be less than 2." Thus we can conlude that we don't have quite enough samples to stratify using SDD

It is important to split our data into a train and test set so that we can accurately assess how are model will do with data that we have never seen before. If we used all of our data to train our models we could be overfitting the data and have models that perform much worse when they are tested on data we haven't seen before.

Linear Regression Model ¶

A linear regression model is a model that attempts to find the linear relationship between the predictors and the response. We find the coefficients of the model by solving for the equation that minimizes the residual sum of squares.

We are just going to run a simple linear regression model

To test this linear model more we are going to be using cross validation with 5 folds. What this means is that we will be splitting our training data set into five different equal sized subsets. Each time we fit our model we will leave our one of the five subsets and then test with the fifth subset. We will do this five times, leaving out one subset at a time for testing

Lasso Regression Model ¶

Lasso Regression is very similiar to the above linear regression except that it has a penalty that shrinks the coefficient terms. The amout the Lasso penalizes is based off of alpha value that goes from 0 to 1.

In the below code we tune the alpha value so that it minimizes the mean squared error for our training set. We again use cross validation.

In [332]:
alphas = np.linspace(0, 0.9, 36)
LassoReg = Lasso()
alpha_df = { 'alpha': np.linspace(0.01, 0.9, 36)}

LassoReg_Tune = GridSearchCV(LassoReg, alpha_df, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', cv=5, n_jobs=-1)

results = LassoReg_Tune.fit(X_train, SDD_train)

best_alpha = results.best_params_['alpha']

print('MSE: ' + str(results.best_score_))
print('Config: ' + str(results.best_params_))

MSE: -10.4566174682388
Config: {'alpha': 0.9}

Now we can use our tuned results to fit our model. The alpha value that was chosen was 0.9. This is to be expected because we have seen by our r squared values in the linear regression model, our model does worse than a model that is just a flat line.

Elastic Net Regression Model ¶

Elastic Net Regression combines Ridge and Lasso regression which helps make our model more robust. It chooses the optimal L1 ration to minimize mean squared error.

In [342]:
#We want to set possible tuning paramters
l1_space = np.linspace(0, 1, 30)
param_grid = {'l1_ratio': l1_space}

#Initialize the model
elastic_net = ElasticNet()

#Create a grid to tune paramters
elastic_cv = GridSearchCV(elastic_net, param_grid, cv = 5)

#Fit given model
elastic_cv.fit(X_train, SDD_train)

#Use fitted model to predict
SDD_pred_ela = elastic_cv.predict(X_test)

r2 = r2_score(SDD_test,SDD_pred_ela)
mse = MSE(SDD_test, SDD_pred_ela)

print("Tuned ElasticNet l1 ratio: {}".format(elastic_cv.best_params_))
print('Using Cross Validation and Tuning the best R2 score was: ' + str(elastic_cv.best_score_))

print("(When tested on test set) R2 Squared Value of Linear Regression Model was: " + str(r2))

Decision Tree Regression Model ¶

A decision tree regression model works by splitting the predictor space so that we minimize the variance of each variable. The tree stops when all of its parameters: maxium depth, minimum number of samplesleaf, and maximum number features is met.

In [344]:
DecTre = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state = 3)
params_dectre = {'max_depth': [3, 4, 5, 6],
             'min_samples_leaf': [0.04, 0.06, 0.08],
             'max_features': [0.2, 0.4,0.6, 0.8]
            }

#Instantiate a 5fold CV grid search object
grid_dectre = GridSearchCV(estimator=DecTre,
                       param_grid=params_dectre,
                       scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',
                       cv=5,
                       n_jobs=-1)

#Fit grid_dectre to the data
grid_dectre.fit(X_train, SDD_train)

best_parameters = grid_dectre.best_params_
print('Using cross validation and tuning the best MSE was: ' + str(grid_dectre.best_score_))
print('Best hyerparameters:\n', best_parameters)

Using cross validation and tuning the best MSE was: -10.960981077688647
Best hyerparameters:
 {'max_depth': 3, 'max_features': 0.2, 'min_samples_leaf': 0.08}

These hyperparameters make sense since we want the lowest depth and least amount of features so we don't box the response into a space that it doesn't actually belong in. The low depth helps us not overfit the data. I would expect if out predictors had more information about our response we would have a max depth greater than 3

Polynomial Regression Model ¶

Polynomial Regression Works similiar to Linear Regression except we also account for any linear relationship one of our predictors taken to the second or third degree could have with our response variable.

In [348]:
#Initialize a polynomial transformation
PolyTran = PolynomialFeatures(degree = 3)

#Transform the predictor variables into a polynomial of degree 3
X_train_poly = PolyTran.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_poly = PolyTran.transform(X_test)

#Initialize polynomial regression
PolyReg = LinearRegression(normalize = True)

#Use cross validation to estimate SDD

PolyReg.fit(X_train_poly,SDD_train)

Best Model ¶

When we look to compare models we have the models with the lowest training MSE to be the Decision Tree Regression Model and the Lasso/Elastic Net Model. We saw above that the Decision Tree Regression Model has an R squared value equal to around 0.345 and a MSE of 7.5. This is much better than the r squared value -0.19 and the MSE of 13.8. Thus we choose the Decision Tree Regression Model as our best model. Let us implement a scatter plot comparing the actual SDD values and the predicted SDD values.

Conclusion ¶

After Several Models and no scores that were much better than random, I have come to the conclusion that this data does not hold very much information about SDD. This does not come as too much of a suprise since we are trying to predict water visibility from buoy data. I do believe that there are ways that exist out there that can help us predict water visibility, however from these scores I do not think looking at buoy data is the correct one. Even though no models did very well, the Decision Tree Regression Model did perform the best by far. This leads me to believe that once I collect better data the Decision Tree Regression Model will be the way to go.
